<TEXT>
<P>
 There are 1,700 lighted street signs in Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
 City officials know because they counted them. 
</P>
<P>
 The city recently calculated the cost of putting block numbers on the large 
brown street-name markers that hang from traffic signals. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials discovered that the numbers can't simply be added to the existing 
signs. Rather, all 1,700 signs would have to be replaced, at a cost of 
$289,000, said Robert W. Tracy, acting public works director. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials also found that adding the block numbers would require reducing the 
size of the letters that spell out the street names. 
</P>
<P>
 Citing a poor "cost-benefit ratio," Tracy is not recommending any change. 
Today 
</P>
<P>
 Looking for a Halloween activity for your kids that won't scare their socks 
off? 
</P>
